Clearly not. The creature was content to whistle and attempted to charge straight at Thassalin. Fortunately, despite its size, it was agile enough to dodge, but Nyssi couldn't help screaming when she almost lost her grip on its too slippery scales.
"HOW DO YOU KILL THEM?" Nyssi cried.
"AIM FOR THEIR HEAD!"
"THIS WON'T BE EASY!"
Thassalin breathed out, then turned around to approach the mountain he called home. The black beast followed, somewhat frantic when a flash of fire hit it from behind. The creature hadn't noticed it was no longer alone. Its frenzy grew when Thassalin slowed down, then struck it violently on the head with his tail, causing it to deviate from its trajectory.
Groaning and hissing, the creature took altitude and spat into the air. Suddenly, everything turned black, as if the monster was sucking in the sky's light and replacing it with a perpetual night cloud.
Having lost all visibility, Thassalin tried to retreat, but scraped the treetops before crashing into the clearing. As if it had exactly known where he had fallen, the creature charged straight at him, dragging the dark cloud in its wake.
"Kayel!" exclaimed Tenuk as he emerged from the cloud and began flying in circles to try and spot Nyssi and Thassalin below, in the darkness. "What's going on, Kayel? Kayel...? Kayel, where are you?"
Down below, Nyssi struggled to get up. She was sure she had broken something, but her strange, unnatural healing powers had already begun to take effect. It wasn't the same for Thassalin, who was lying on a stump, leaning against the only tree that hadn't bent under his weight. Nyssi did her best to try and reach Thassalin, but she couldn't see more than two meters in front of her. Everything was plunged into darkness, swallowed up in the evil shadows. And in those shadows, something was screaming.
A horrible whip-like tail came crashing down beside Nyssi, knocking her to the ground. However, she noted that the tail was thrashing about, not targeting her. The creature, from what Nyssi could see and hear, was growling and scratching at the shadows it had created. Something was teleporting through the darkness, hitting the monster, disorienting it.
A sudden gunshot rang out, and the monster collapsed silently, inert. The darkness surrounding them dissipated, revealing what had just happened. Standing over the creature was Kayel, gun in hand and breathing heavily.
"That's... the strangest shadow jump I've ever made... Thanto kat'olon...", Kayel gasped. His eyes shone with a dark light, and a dark energy ran through his body. However, as he spoke, Kayel's organic plating regained its color, and his eyes returned to their normal yellow color.
It took Nyssi a moment to understand what had happened. They all knew that Kayel possessed strange shadow powers. He used them rarely, as most people considered them impious and frightening. But Nyssi ignored that Kayel could use these powers in the dark. And, judging by his behavior, Kayel seemed just as surprised himself.
"Are you okay?" Nyssi couldn't help but ask.
"Yes, I'm fine. I killed something. It will be better in a minute." Kayel examined his work, while Tenuk made his way to land beside him, returning to his normal form of Spast.
Now that the creature wasn't moving anymore, they could see what it was. Its skin was black like coal and sticky, but the saliva continued to adhere to its body. It had four wings and four limbs, all ending in long claws, and two straight horns protruded from its skull.
Before Tenuk and Kayel could ask what that thing was, something screamed and launched itself from a nearby bush. However, the beast didn't have time to reach them, as a familiar vehicle crashed into its side, throwing it at Nyssi's feet. Not taking any risks, she grabbed her gun and shot it immediately in the head, killing the creature on the spot.
"Oops...", muttered Retvik from the driver's seat, before clumsily turning off the engine and jumping out of the truck. "I, uh, didn't mean to do that. Are you guys okay?"
"You practically missed the whole action," Tenuk regretted. "Where were you?"
"You guys dropped me. I came here as fast as I could," Retvik sighed. "Can someone tell us what those abhorrent things are?"
Fortunately, Retvik's question received an answer from Thassalin, who had just gotten up. He was all cut up and scratched all over and seemed a bit disoriented, but he didn't seem too badly hurt.
"YOU KILLED THE CORRUPTIIDS! THE INFECTED MONSTERS. CREATURES LEFT HERE WHEN CORRUPTION ATTACKED YOUR GODS."
"You mean... the horrible god monster that we... helped kill?", stuttered Tenuk.
"Yes. Exactly. There might be others, but I didn't manage to hit them in the head. I'm missing a gun. Plus, two against one isn't fair, is it?" Thassalin walked over to Kayel and patted him on the head. "Thanks, little one. You remind me of my old friend Arkadin. But less murderous and less capable of killing universes."
"Uh... thanks... I suppose", said Kayel with a shrug. "So, we're done here?"
Nissy shrugged, then took out her camera to photograph the now-dead creatures. She then pulled out her favorite dagger, the god of death's dagger, and began to cut off one of the creature's horns, before moving on to the other. But as she finished, the creatures ignited and quickly turned into piles of ashes. The same thing happened to the horns Nyssi had cut off.
"Well... it's both convenient and not convenient at all," she sighed. "At least, I still have the photos..."
